\par \pard\plain \f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} DOS box (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} DosBox}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:dosbox}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} DOS box}} A {\b DOS Box}
 is a Microsoft Windows feature within which DOS programs are executed. In Windows "386-enhanced" mode, a DOS box ca
n appear as an icon, a window or it can occupy the whole screen. In Windows "standard" mode, DOS programs can execute only when their DOS box occupies the whole screen.
\par \pard\plain \s6 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Under Windows NT, the equivalent of DOS Boxes are named "shell boxes"
\par \pard \s6 {\fs16\up6 \page ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Commands (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Command}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:command}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} commands;macro}} {\b Commands}
 are built in functions that represent basic things that MicroEMACS does. For example, the up arrow key activates the "previous-line" command which moves the cursor up to the line of text immediately before the current line.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Binding (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Binding}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:binding}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} binding}} A {\b binding} is a link
 between a sequence of keys and a command or macro. For instance, the command "previous-line" is bound to the up-arrow key, and to the ^P key. Pressing a key sequence causes the command to which it is bound to execute.
\par \pard \s6\sl240 Under Microsoft Windows, commands and macros can also be bound to menu items.
\par \pard \s6 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Meta key (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} MetaKey}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:metakey}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} meta key}} The {\b meta key}
 is the key used to start many commands. On most keyboards this is the Escape key, but many times it is rebound/changed to the key in the upper left corner of the keyboard. This is often the grave accent symbol.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Numeric argument (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Argument}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:argument}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} numeric argument}} Interactively, a {\b numeric argument}
 is supplied by typing the meta key (usually the Escape key), followed by a decimal number, before invoking a command.
\par \pard \s6 Within the macro language, a numeric argument is placed before the name of the associated command.
\par \pard \s6 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Buffers (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Buffer}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:buffer}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} buffer}} {\b Buffers}
 are areas of memory set aside to hold text. Each buffer has a buffer name which is used to refer to it, and a file name from which it has been read or where it will be written.
\par \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Popup buffers (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} PopupBuffer}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:popupbuffer}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} popup buffer}} {\b Popup Buffers} are a way t
o display a buffer temporarily, without using a window. When a popup buffer is displayed, it occupies the whole screen. If more than one screenfull is needed, the text "-- more --" appears on the message line. The next screenfull can be viewed by pressing
 the space bar. Pressing any other key cancels the popup buffer and the keystroke is then processed  by MicroEMACS.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Windows (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Window}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:window}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} window}} {\b Windows}
 are sections of the current screen which display a portion of a buffer. More than one window may be visible at a time. Multiple windows split the screen horizontally.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Notice that the MicroEMACS usage of the word window is different from the meaning used in window-based systems:
\par \pard\plain \s11\li360\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\ul MicroEMACS}\tab {\ul Operating System}
\par Window\tab Pane
\par Screen\tab Window
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Screens (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Screen}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote 
\pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:screen}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} screen}} {\b Screens}
 are collections of windows. On a older text style system, one screen is displayed at a time. On a newer window based system, like OS/2, the Macintosh or Microsoft Windows, each operating system window can display a different MicroEMACS screen.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 Notice that the MicroEMACS usage of the word window is different from the meaning used in window-based systems:
\par \pard\plain \s11\li360\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\ul MicroEMACS}\tab {\ul Operating System}
\par Window\tab Pane
\par Screen\tab Window
\par \pard\plain \s6 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Mode line (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} ModeLine}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:modeline}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} mode line}} The {\b mode line}
 is the line at the bottom of each window naming the buffer being displayed, along with its file name. Also the active modes of the window are shown.
\par \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Message line (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} MessageLine}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:messageline}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} message line;command line}} The {\b command line} or{\b  message line}
 is the line at the bottom of the screen where you give more information to some commands and also receive information or error messages.
\par \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Macro (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Macro}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +}
 Glossary:macro}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} macro}} {\b Macros} (also called {\b procedures}
) are programs written in the MicroEMACS language which let you customize the editor and, in particular, automate repetitive editing tasks.\page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Keyboard macro (glossary)}} {
\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} KeyboardMacro}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:keyboardmacro}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 K} keyboard macro;macro}} A {\b keyboard macro} is a remembered sequence of keystrokes which can be used to greatly speed quick and dirty repetitive editing.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Page (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Page}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:page}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} page;macro}} {\b Pages}
 are groups of macros which have been written to handle a particular editing task, and which have been packaged to be available from the MicroEMACS startup file. These files usually have a filename extension of ".CMD".
\par \pard \s6 The MS-Windows version of MicroEMACS is bundled with sample macro pages called CUA.CMD, DEV.CMD and MDI.CMD.
\par \pard \s6 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Path (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Path}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:path}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} path}} The {\b path} is a list of directories that MicroEMACS searches for the following files:
\par \pard\plain \s11\li360\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 EMACS.RC (the startup file)
\par The argument of the execute-file command
\par The argument of the &find function
\par The default DOSEXEC.PIF and DOSBOX.PIF files
\par \pard \s11\li360\sa120\tx2880 EMACS.HLP (for the help command)
\par \pard\plain \s6 \f2\fs20\lang1033 The following items compose the {\b path} (in order of decreasing priority):
\par \pard\plain \s8\fi-360\li360\tx360\tx1440\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320 \f2\fs20\lang1033 1.\tab The directory specified by the HOME system variable (or, under MS-Windows, the directory where the MicroEMACS executable resides).
\par 2.\tab The current working directory.
\par 3.\tab The directories specified in the PATH system variable.
\par 4.\tab The following directories (MS-DOS-based or Windows NT systems only. Other implementations use different lists):
\par \pard\plain \s13\fi-2880\li2880\tx900\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \tab \\sys\\public
\par \tab \\usr\\bin
\par \tab \\bin
\par \tab \\
\par \pard\plain \s6 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Point (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Point}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:point}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} point}} The {\b point}
 is the position of the cursor in the text of the current window. The point can be considered to lie between the character the cursor rests on and the one immediately after it.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Mark (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Mark}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:mark}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} mark;region}} The {\b mark }
is the position in the current buffer which delimits the beginning or the end of a region. Various commands operate on text from the mark to the point, or move the current point to the mark. The mark can be set by the set-mark command.
\par \pard \s6 Each buffer contains 16 independent marks, numbered 0 to 15. Most region-related commands, however, only refer to mark 0.
\par Marks 10 to 15 are reserved for use by macros. Marks 0 to 9 are reserved for interactive use.
\par Marks 11 and 12 are used internally by MicroEMACS by the mouse-region-down and mouse-region-up commands.
\par \pard \s6 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Region (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Region}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:region}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} region;mark}} A {\b region}
 is the text located between the point (i.e. the position of the cursor) and the mark number 0. The mark can be set by the set-mark command.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Selection (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Selection}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:selection}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} selection;clipboard}} The {\b selection}
 is available only if the macros from the CUA.CMD page have been loaded. It is the piece of text that has been selected by dragging the mouse (with the left button held down) over it, or by moving (with the arrow or the page keys) thr
ough the text with the Shift key held down.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 The CUA.CMD file is distributed as part of the MicroEMACS for Windows package.
\par \pard \s6 In the current version of MicroEMACS, the selection is not highlighted.
\par \pard \s6 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Clipboard (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Clipboard}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:clipboard}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} clipboard;selection}} The {\b clipboard}
 is a temporary storage area. Text can be cut or copied to the clipboard from a Windows application and be pasted into another application.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Variables (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Variable}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:variable}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} variable;macro}} {\b Variables} are elements of the MicroEMACS macro language. They carry numeric, boolean or string values.

\par \pard \s6 Variables that begin with a dollar sign "{\b $}" are called environmental variables. They control various aspects of the editor.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Functions (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Function}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:function}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} function;macro}} {\b Functions}
 are elements of the MicroEMACS macro language. Functions have arguments and return numeric, boolean or string values.
\par \pard \s6 Function names begin by an ampersand "{\b &}". Only the first 3 characters of a function name are significant.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Groups (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Group}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 
{\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:group}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} group;search;replace}} {\b Groups}
 can be used with text substitution commands or macros in MAGIC mode, to duplicate parts of the target into the result.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 In the search string, a group is defined as a portion beginning by the characters backlash and opening parenthesis "{\b \\(}" and ended by the characters backlash and closing parenthesis "{\b \\)}". There can be up to nine such groups.

\par In the replace string, groups appear as a backlash followed by a decimal digit ("{\b \\1}" to "{\b \\9}"). The portion of the target string matched by the {\i n}{\fs18\up6 th} group is substituted to each occurrence of \\{\i n}
 to form the replacement string.
\par \pard \s6 The function &group {\i n} can be used in macros to obtain the text matched by the {\i n}{\fs18\up6 th} group in a search.
