\par \pard \s6\sa120 {\fs16 \page }{\b\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Kill Buffer (glossary)}}{\fs16  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} KillBuffer}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote 
\pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:killbuffer}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} kill;copy;move;delete}} The {\b kill buffer}
 accumulates any text which is "killed" by a number of delete commands. If more than one delete command is used in a row, all the text fro
m all the commands will be in the kill buffer. Using any command between deletes causes the kill buffer to just hold the most recent deletions.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 
Using this feature and the yank command, you can switch between windows, screens and files and copy text from one file to another.There is no limit to the amount of text that can be stored in the kill buffer except that of the memory of the computer runni
ng MicroEMACS. Extremely large kills may take a few seconds.
\par \pard \s6 The last 16 kill buffers are kept in the kill ring. You can retrieve their contents through the cycle-ring or the yank-pop commands.
\par \pard \s6 \page {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Kill Ring (glossary)}} {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} KillRing}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 
{\fs16\up6 +} Glossary:killring}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} kill;copy;move;delete}} The {\b kill ring}
 is a circular list of the last 16 kill buffers. The position of the current kill buffer can be changed by the cycle-ring and the yank-pop commands. The kill ring can be emptied (and thus the used memory reclaimed) by using the delete-kill-ring command.

